data.body:
Hi,

I have an application that renders text to the screen.
I have a class called TextVisual that represents a single text element on the screen 
with properties such as width, height, x, y, alignment, font, etc...

The Draw() method basically looks like this:

``` csharp
GraphicsDevice.Clear(Color.Black);
spriteBatch.Begin(SpriteSortMode.Immediate, BlendState.AlphaBlend, null, null, _rasterizerState);

for (int i = 0; i < Fields.Count; i++)
{
    Fields[i].Draw(spriteBatch);
}

spriteBatch.End();

base.Draw(gameTime);

```

And the Draw() method of the TextVisual class looks like this

``` csharp
if (ActiveData[displayedChannel] != null && Font != null)
{
    batch.GraphicsDevice.ScissorRectangle = new Rectangle((int)Position.X, (int)Position.Y, Width, Height);
    batch.DrawString(Font, ActiveData[displayedChannel], new Vector2(Position.X + textOffSetX, Position.Y + textOffSetY), ActiveColors[displayedChannel], Rotation, Origin, Scale, Effects, 0);
}

/* Anything beyond this line is only used for debugging and not used when my issue occurs
   however, when this code does run, the text is rendered properly, but when the flags are disabled
   artifacts remain on the screen anyway */
if ((Debug & DebugInfoVisibility.RectangleOverlay) == DebugInfoVisibility.RectangleOverlay)
{
    if (debugOverlayTexture == null)
    {
        debugOverlayTexture = new Texture2D(batch.GraphicsDevice, 1, 1, false, SurfaceFormat.Color);
        debugOverlayTexture.SetData(new[] { Color.FromNonPremultiplied(0, 0 , 255, 200) });
    }

    batch.Draw(debugOverlayTexture, new Rectangle((int)Position.X, (int)Position.Y, Width, Height), Color.White);
}

if ((Debug & DebugInfoVisibility.DefinitionInfo) == DebugInfoVisibility.DefinitionInfo)
{
        var text = String.Format("{0}, {1}x{2} ({3},{4}) XO:{5}, YO:{6}, C:{7}", 
                                Id, Width, Height, Position.X, Position.Y, textOffSetX, textOffSetY, displayedChannel);
    batch.DrawString(OverlayFont, text, new Vector2(Position.X + 2, Position.Y + 4), Color.Yellow);

}

if ((Debug & DebugInfoVisibility.RectangleBorder) == DebugInfoVisibility.RectangleBorder)
{
    DrawingHelper.DrawRectangleAroundVisual(this, batch, Color.Yellow, 1);
}
```

On Windows (XNA) this works just fine.
Text is rendered to the screen and scrolls from right to left

On Linux however, only the last field in the array is rendered properly
and all the fields before that... well it looks to me that with every call to draw()
the text is rendered at the new position but the old text is not cleared from the screen
which in the end results in one big white block (if the text is white)

I have a video showing the same application side-by-side on Windows and Linux
https://skydrive.live.com/redir?resid=B4D2AF3D00C31E69!478

If I enable the debug features, as long as I don't disable them, the text is rendered properly
behind the debuy overlay rectangles. As soon as I disable the debug features, the rectangle
remains visible on all items except for the last one and the text issues start again

If I then enable the debug features again, everything gets messed up.

What could be causing this behavior?

Another question: is this a good way to render scrolling text within a defined space on the screen
or are there better ways?

After updating to the most recent version of the develop3d branch, I'm no longer able to resize the game window using the following code in my game class Initialize() method if placed after the base.Initialize() call. It does still work when placed before the base.Initialize() call however.

``` C#
Graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = 1024;
Graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = 768;
Graphics.ApplyChanges();
```

I seem to be encountering significant memory leaks when drawing to a RenderTexture2D. My UI framework uses this a lot to layer up interface elements, etc. On Windows my memory usage stays at around 70 megs, on OS X it shoots up beyond 500.

Here's an example of what I'm doing:

```
        //Class constructor:
        _texture=new RenderTarget2D(VideoManager.Graphics.GraphicsDevice,
        _frame.Width,
        _partHeight,
        false,
        VideoManager.Graphics.GraphicsDevice.PresentationParameters.BackBufferFormat,
        VideoManager.Graphics.GraphicsDevice.PresentationParameters.DepthStencilFormat,
        VideoManager.Graphics.GraphicsDevice.PresentationParameters.MultiSampleCount,
        RenderTargetUsage.PreserveContents);


        //Redraw method:
        VideoManager.Graphics.GraphicsDevice.SetRenderTarget(_texture);
        SpriteBatch sb=new SpriteBatch(VideoManager.Graphics.GraphicsDevice);

        try {
            sb.Begin();
            //Drawing code here
            sb.End();
        } finally {
            sb.Dispose();
        }
        sb = null;
        VideoManager.Graphics.GraphicsDevice.SetRenderTarget(null);
```

In the latest develop3d commit, OpenTKGamePlatform.cs won't compile.

Line 254 - 261:

```
    protected override void OnIsMouseVisibleChanged()
    {
        MouseState oldState = Mouse.GetState();
        _view.Window.CursorVisible = IsMouseVisible;
        // IsMouseVisible changes the location of the cursor on Linux (and Windows?) and we have to manually set it back to the correct position
        System.Drawing.Point mousePos = _view.Window.PointToScreen(new System.Drawing.Point(oldState.X, oldState.Y));
        OpenTK.Input.Mouse.SetPosition(mousePos.X, mousePos.Y);
    }
```

+view.Window.CursorVisible is not defined,
OpenTK.Input.Mouse.SetPosition() is not defined.

In Windows 8 you have to hook up the Window.ClientSizeChanged event to check if the ApplicationView.Value is Snapped or Filled, but some of the last PR added a bug to it. This is what I was doing:
this.Window.ClientSizeChanged += Window_ClientSizeChanged;
And the handler has doing this:
            if (ApplicationView.Value == Windows.UI.ViewManagement.ApplicationViewState.Snapped)
            {
                graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = 320;
                graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = 800;
                graphics.ApplyChanges();
            }
            else
            {
                graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = 1280;
                graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = 800;
                graphics.ApplyChanges();
            }
            this.GraphicsDevice.Viewport = new Viewport(0, 0, graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth, graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight);

But now if I call ApplyChanges, screen turns Black and stops showing anything. I realized that this happens until I change the RenderTarget, so I think this have something to do with the graphics not updating correctly.
To fix it I just stoped calling ApplyChanges, and it IS working, but not the expected code behaviour.
Anyone knows what may be causing this?

Tnx in advance!
